pr_review_comment_body:
As the timestamp could have different scalars for different serial devices (which I'm not entirely sure is reasonable), then we should allow the user to inform the `Serial` class of this scalar to ensure that when serializing/deserializing a frame we apply a correction to the timestamp.

Even if we set some standard (e.g. integer microseconds), there will be some smarter devices (e.g. a raspberry pi) which will actually have epoch time, and some use cases that will want to collect more than `MAX_INT` microseconds. 

@christiansandberg care to weigh in here?

Make `remove` a `list` instead of a `bool`?

```
d = {}

if remove:
    for item in remove:
        try:
            items.remove(item)
        except ValueError:
            pass

    tag_name = '%s[].tag.tag-' % tag
    d[tag_name] = ','.join(remove)

for i, item in enumerate(items):
    tag_name = '%s[%s].tag.tag' % (tag, i)
    d[tag_name] = item

d['%s.locked' % tag] = 1 if locked else 0

return d
````

Just in case this list of intraday frequency every changes, we'd like to make the code change once in both places (here and in the frequency validation function). We can do

```python
if self._is_intraday_frequency(frequency):
    return "iex/{}/prices"
else:
   return "tiingo/daily/{}/prices" 

def _is_intraday_frequency(frequency):
    return frequency.lower() in ['daily', 'weekly', 'monthly', 'annually']
```

